03808nam a22004935i 9780520966574DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209665747 a10.1525/97805209665742doi  a(DE-B1597)518626  a(OCoLC)1038495282  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aMUS0280002bisacsh1 aSmart, Mary Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aWaiting for Verdi :bOpera and Political Opinion in Nineteenth-Century Italy, 1815-1848 /cMary Ann Smart. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Risorgimento Fantasies -- t2. Accidental Affinities: Gioachino Rossini and Salvatore Viganò -- t3. Elizabeth I, Mary Stuart, and the Limits of Allegory -- t4. Reading Mazzini's "Filosofia della musica" with Byron and Donizetti -- t5. Parlor Games -- t6. Progress, Piety, and Plagiarism: Verdi's I Lombardi at La Scala -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe name Giuseppe Verdi conjures images of Italians singing opera in the streets and bursting into song at political protests or when facing the firing squad. While many of the accompanying stories were exaggerated, or even invented, by later generations, Verdi's operas-along with those by Rossini, Donizetti, and Mercadante-did inspire Italians to imagine Italy as an independent and unified nation. Capturing what it was like to attend the opera or to join in the music at an aristocratic salon, Waiting for Verdi shows that the moral dilemmas, emotional reactions, and journalistic polemics sparked by these performances set new horizons for what Italians could think, feel, say, and write. Among the lessons taught by this music were that rules enforced by artistic tradition could be broken, that opera could jolt spectators into intense feeling even as it educated them, and that Italy could be in the vanguard of stylistic and technical innovation rather than clinging to the glories of centuries past. More practically, theatrical performances showed audiences that political change really was possible, making the newly engaged spectator in the opera house into an actor on the political stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520966574423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520966574.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles